{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"93f056d8-4e7b-46f9-8b8d-6781f5b9941f","content":"**Use `dotnet workload update`.**\n\nAfter a .NET SDK update, the installed workloads (like `maui`) can fall out of sync with the new SDK version. Here's the difference:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads, matching them to your current SDK. This is what you want after an SDK update.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs the **currently recorded versions** of workloads. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but doesn't upgrade anything.\n\n**Recommended steps:**\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf the build still fails after updating, also try `dotnet workload restore` in your project directory — it will install any workloads declared in your project's `global.json` or implied by your target frameworks.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"88064a6a-2039-497a-be0e-04499e7adf54","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI workload management — specifically whether to use `dotnet workload update` or `dotnet workload repair` after a SDK update broke their build. This is a general knowledge question, not a codebase task.","outputTokens":272,"requestId":"9812:375CFA:159A783:1823981:6A051DA0"},"id":"d2eb1e4f-b300-44a5-99aa-82342a33fc51","timestamp":"2026-05-14T00:56:09.416Z","parentId":"b732f2d8-cab1-47d4-b23f-76b4feec21c9"}
